{{Coord|31|46|34.18|N|35|10|46.94|E|region:IL_type:mountain|display=title}}
{{Infobox monument |monument_name = Garden of the Missing in Action |native_name = גן הנעדרים |image = גן הנעדרים - הר הרצל 1.jpg |caption = |coordinates = {{coord|31|46|29.97|N|35|10|40.86|E|region:IL_type:mountain|display=inline}} |location = [[Mount Herzl]], [[Jerusalem]] |designer = |type = |material = |length = |width = |height = |begin = |complete = 2004 |open = |dedicated_to = the [[Missing in action]] that burial place is unknown |map_image = |map_text = |map_width = |relief = |extra = }}
[[File:גן הנעדרים - מצבות 1.jpg|thumb|290px|left|Empty Grave markers in the Garden of the Missing Soldiers]] The '''Garden of the Missing in Action''' ({{lang-he|גן הנעדרים}}, ''Gan HaNe'edarim'', Garden of the Missing ones) is an [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier|unknown soldier memorial]] and commemorative garden on [[Mount Herzl]] in [[Jerusalem]] dedicated to [[Israeli MIAs]].
The garden memorializes fighters and officers of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] and [[Land of Israel|pre-state]] MIAs starting from 1914, whose resting place is unknown.<ref>[http://www.boeliem.com/content/2004/704.html Mount Herzl: The Creation of Israel's National Cemetery Mount Herzl]</ref> The garden was inaugurated in February 2004 in a ceremony attended by army chiefs, the Israeli [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Defense Minister]] [[Shaul Mofaz]], and members of the [[Jerusalem Municipality]]. The garden also contains memorials to those lost aboard the submarine [[INS Dakar|INS ''Dakar'']] and the [[Operation Boatswain|''"23 Who Went Down at Sea"]] of May 1941. Since the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948, over 400 Israeli soldiers have been declared "Missing in Action."{{fact|date=June 2013}} The construction of the Garden of the Missing on Mt. Herzl was initiated and headed by [[Moshe Oren]], as head of the Ministry of Defense Commemoration Division.
An annual memorial service for the Missing Soldiers of Israel takes place in the garden's main plaza on the [[Seventh of Adar]], the day in the Hebrew calendar which marks the traditional date of the death of [[Moses]], whose grave is known only to God, according to the [[Hebrew Bible]].
