{{Italic title}}
'''''The Breakdown''''' was a 1926 painting by Scottish artist [[John Bulloch Souter]] (1890–1972) which stirred controversy in the [[United Kingdom]] during the [[Jazz Age]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2018}}{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} The work depicted a musician playing the [[saxophone]] while a naked woman dances in a trance.{{sfn|Shearer|2018}}{{sfn|Toepfer|1997|p=364}} Following widespread outrage, the painting was withdrawn from the [[Royal Academy Summer Exhibition]] in 1926 after one week at the request of the British [[Colonial Office]] as the subject matter "was considered to be obnoxious to British subjects living abroad in daily contact with a coloured population".{{sfn|Tackley|2005|p=188}}{{sfn|Parsonage|2007|page=95}} The painting was then destroyed by its author and his wife,{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} but Souter preserved his preparatory drawings and made a second version in the 1960s.{{sfn|Shearer|2018}} The painting has been described as embodying the fears of Western civilization towards [[jazz]] music.{{sfn|Blake|1999|p=89}}

==Description==
In Souter's painting, an [[androgynous]] woman dancer has short [[bob cut|shingled]] hair,{{sfn|Tackley|2005|p=188}} and her eyes are closed, as if she is in a [[trance]].{{sfn|Toepfer|1997|p=364}} Her discarded clothes and shoes lie on the ground, with just one green earring visible. The musician is in full [[white tie]] evening dress with a [[top hat]]; he sits on a cast down and broken classical statue of possibly [[Minerva]], the goddess of virginity and traditional values.{{sfn|Tackley|2005|p=188}}{{sfn|Parsonage|2007|page=95}}{{sfn|Blake|1999|p=89}} The musician is black and the woman is white, playing on contemporaneous concerns about the popularity of (largely black) [[jazz music]] to the (largely white) British public, and the perceived threat posed by black men to white women.{{sfn|McKay|2018}} According to Karl Toepfer, "the musician gazes not at the woman but out toward the spectator, and the implication is that jazz and dance together allow man and woman to cross racial barriers and form a new and mysteriously intimate (or trusting) sort of couple, each immersed in separate aspirations."{{sfn|Toepfer|1997|p=364}}

Souter's stated intention was to "illustrate the tendency nowadays for Jazz influence to permeate our daily lives",{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} and to "suggest the fascination exercised by the primitive and savage upon the over-civilised".{{sfn|Shearer|2018}}  The title is a reference to a [[African-American dance|slave dance]] called the "break down", and to the breakdown of traditions.

==Exhibition==
The painting was exhibited at the [[Royal Academy Summer Exhibition]] starting on 3 May 1926, the day before the start of the [[1926 United Kingdom general strike|1926 General Strike]].  The painting was viewed by King [[George V]] and praised by the [[President of the Royal Academy]], [[Frank Dicksee]], as "a work of great promise by executed with a considerable degree of excellence".{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} However, the world press fixated upon the painting and its exhibition quickly became controversial.{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} According to Catherine Tackley, professor of music at the [[University of Liverpool]], "the reaction to the painting epitomises the response to this new jazz music. Huge popular enthusiasm – and an undercurrent of suspicion that this was a dangerous new art form subverting decent society."{{sfn|Kennedy|2018}} The work was widely condemned in British newspapers and periodicals. In an early edition of the ''[[Melody Maker]]'', a British weekly [[music journalism|music magazine]], London-born critic Edgar Jackson demanded the painting be encindered:

{{quote|{{resize|90%|"‘Breakdown’ is not only a picture entirely nude of the respect due to the chastity and morality of the younger generation but in the degradation it implies to modern white woman there is the perversive danger to the community and the best thing that could happen to it is to have it … burnt!"{{sfn|McKay|2018}}{{sfn|Shearer|2018}}}}}}

In the [[United States of America]], the ''[[Boston Evening Transcript]]'' criticised the work under the headline "A Racial Outrage" and claimed the painting was designed "to horrify decent people".{{sfn|Kennedy|2018}} Likewise, in South Africa, the ''[[Cape Argus]]'' deemed the work to be a "problem picture … Negro Supersedes Minerva".{{sfn|Kennedy|2018}} Ultimately, the painting was removed after only five days at the request of the [[Colonial Office]] and replaced by a portrait of Lady [[Diana Manners]] by [[James Jebusa Shannon]].{{sfn|McKay|2005|pp=121-22}}

Souter and his wife Christian Grace Reid destroyed his original 1926 painting,{{sfn|Rendezvous Gallery|1918}} but Souter kept his preparatory drawings.{{sfn|Kennedy|2018}} For decades it was only known from a photograph published in the exhibition catalogue, but Souter made a second version in the 1960s.{{sfn|Shearer|2018}} A charcoal study was acquired by the Aberdeen Art Gallery in 2016, with funding from the Scottish [[National Fund for Acquisitions]].{{sfn|Aberdeen Art Gallery|1918}}

==Legacy and influence==
[[Evelyn Waugh]] attended the exhibition in its first week. The controversy over the painting may have inspired him to include a mixed-race relationship between the white Margot and black Chokey in his 1928 novel ''[[Decline and Fall]]''.

